<div xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><head n="1">Introduction</head><p>This paper presents a fast method for producing a bi level image portraying field strength and three dimensional orientation. The image produced is suitable for a laser printer or bitmapped display. The method is appropriate for displaying a field that has been either measured or com puted, on a grid of moderate resolution (sizes greater than roughly 70x70 require larger format than the 6" normally used on a printed page). The method is appropriate for three dimensional vector fields, such as electromagnetic fields or flow fields; electric fields are used for illustrative purposes.</p><p>Two dimensional vector fields are commonly displayed using contour maps (of potential) or stream lines. Contour maps are good for displaying the gradient and direction of a field, but to read field strength from a contour map is more difficult. Streamlines give a more intuitive sense of field strength and direction, but the orientation information is lost where the lines are either too sparse or too dense.</p><p>Several recent approaches simulate in one way or another the effect of visualizing a magnetic field using iron filings on a sheet of paper <ref type="bibr" target="#b7">[8,</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b3">4]</ref>. Adding the extra information required to display orientation within a slice of a three dimensional field is difficult.</p><p>Hedgehogging has been used by Forrest <ref type="bibr" target="#b0">[1]</ref> and others as a means of displaying normal vector information at CH3046-0191/000010148I$Ol.00@ 1991 IEEE Display of slices of a field using hedge hogging is most effective on a fast graphics workstation. so that the entire slice can be rotated and translated in real time. In this way motion augments any other depth cues to give a clear impression of orientation in 3-space. To provide a similar level of information on paper. we introduce shadows.</p></div>
<div xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><head>148</head><p>This paper describes our technique for rapidly obtaining images of hedgehogging with shadows. It begins with a discussion of the requirements for readability. Once the desired image has been described, we show how to compute such an image efficiently. Finally, we discuss the relative merits of the method, and future work.</p></div>
<div xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><head n="2">Readable hedgehogs</head><p>This section addresses issues of making the image read able, in the sense that no information is added (that the eye notices), and as much information is displayed as possible.</p><p>The size of an individual vector must be less than that of the grid spacing. <ref type="figure">Figure I</ref> shows the problems that can result if it is greater than the grid spacing. The size is  the distance of one grid space, lines should not be more than 112 of one grid space. We assume that the maximum field strength is known a priori, so that the vectors drawn can be scaled accordingly. If this is not known, a prep ass through the data is required.   <ref type="figure" target="#fig_5">Figure 4</ref> shows the bulb case at a smaller scale. By varying the length of the line or wedge. some field intensity information can be encoded. Note that wedges must become narrower as they become shorter, so that the base is never longer than the height. Should the base become longer than the height, the perceived orientation is parallel to the base, rather than toward the tip. For lack of a better term, we shall call the bulb-headed representation a thermometer, since it resembles a mercury thermometer. <ref type="figure" target="#fig_7">Figure 5</ref> shows the improvement gained by adding shadows.</p><formula xml:id="formula_0">---------------- ---------------- ---------------- ----------------</formula><formula xml:id="formula_1">\ \ 149 � • " � r".-.-.... .. . ..-..-....-....-...-.... .. . - .. \ , r" .... . -..---..------- .... . .... .. ,--..-..-�.-...-..------.- ,I&gt; , \ '-.... .. . .... .. . .... .... .. _ .... .... . _ .... . .... . .- ,. , � .... .... " .... .. .... .. .... . .... .. .... .... . .... -</formula><p>t For very oblique lighting angles, the sphere casts an elliptical shadow. We limit the angles for light sources so that the circular approximation for the shadow is good. The main reason for limiting light source angles in this way is to prevent the shadows from overlapping.</p><formula xml:id="formula_2">_ � � � � / I t 1 \ \ , _ _ � � � I t 1 1 1 � � _ _ � � � i t � i � � �</formula><p>Shadows are realistic only for (portions ot) thermome ters above the plane of the paper, corresponding to vectors going into the plane of the page. For vectors coming out of the plane of the page, we could draw the shadows as if there were a second light source shining toward the first, and the page were semi-transparent. In this case it would be unclear whether the thermometers point into or out of the plane. To remedy this, we displace them slightly from the plane of the page <ref type="figure">(Figure 6</ref>). The t1lermometers are then seen to float above the plane with th r shadows below II I � � � � � � � � � � ? � � � I I I ! } I I � � A � � � � � � � � � , � , I I I ! } I I t I A 6 � � � � ���" " / I J J � I I � � � � � � � ��.���" , I I I ! . �</p><formula xml:id="formula_3">--� � � � � � � � � � --� � � � � � � � � �</formula><p>.� .� .-: ., l I , I . 1 l ., ., ,\ , .'" .... .... ... �-::-!" ., ,!' � I ' 1. 1 � �:-..</p></div>
