>(Figure 7, right)</ref>.</p><p>Once the vectors' projections and shadows have been determined they can be drawn. A compact but somewhat slow way to do this is to issue PostScript commands to draw the thermometers and their shadows as lines and circles. A much faster technique is to precompute raster images for the set of possible vectors and shadows. The table of these images is then indexed by orientation and length, and the appropriate image is copied to the display.</p><p>Our implementation of this technique can image a 32x32 array of thermometers and their shadows in less than .06 seconds on a Sun 4/260. The shadows are drawn first, so that vectors hide them wherever they overlap.</p></div>
<div xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><head n="4">Discussion</head><p>We  <ref type="table">I I I 1 I , I I , I , I !   1 I I I I 1 I I , , , I I I I 1  I I I I I I I I I I 1' 1 ! 1 1   1 I I I I I I , I I I I I I I I I   1 1 I I I I I I I I I , I ,I ,/ I</ref>  This problem was addressed in our method by restrictmg the lengths of vectors.</p></div>
<div xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><head>152</head><p>Increasing the resolution of the printer allows for an improved resolution in the orientation and intensity infor mation, however this does not allow larger data sets since vectors cannot be drawn much smaller than as shown in <ref type="figure">Figure 6</ref> and still remain useful. With sufficient resolution, it might be possible to introduce the necessary grey levels to provide depth cueing.</p></div><figure xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="fig_0"><head></head><label></label><figDesc>•-------T vertices of a surface, and more recently it has been used in visualization products (one example being Stardent's AVS) to illustrate slices of three dimensional fields. Hedgehog gingtypically done with line segments originating on a surface and directed parallel to the vectors they portray is a three dimensional analog of an old technique. Edmund Halley used pen strokesshort dashes, thicker at one end and tapering to a point at the otherto show prevailing wind direction on a map of the world's oceans (3) (Halley's map is discussed in Tufte (7)). Short lines from each grid point have been used as well (6); line length was tied to field strength with reasonable results in regions of low field strength, less so in regions of high field strength, where the picture becomes cluttered. Lavin and Cherveney have used the density of line segments, rather than their length. to display the field intensity (5).</figDesc></figure>
<figure xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="fig_1"><head>Figure 1</head><label>1</label><figDesc>The clutter that can result from too fine a grid relative to the maximum vector length. The problem is especially pronounced in the region on the left, where vectors converge.actually better kept well below grid spacing, to prevent the visual system from attempting to connect unrelated lines.</figDesc></figure>
<figure xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="fig_2"><head>Figure 2</head><label>2</label><figDesc>illustrates this. If the orientation can reverse in</figDesc></figure>
<figure xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="fig_3"><head>Figure 2</head><label>2</label><figDesc>If the grid spacing is approximately equal to the vector length, the problems of Figure 1 are eliminated, but orientation is obscured by the visual system's attempt to connect straight lines. It is much easier to see straight horizontal lines in an image like the one above, than to discern field orientation. This effect increases with image size. In order to disambiguate orientation. especially in re gions of uniform orientation and strength, the lines need some distinguishing feature at one end. Figure 3 shows three possibilities. According to Fowler and Ware [2], lines of varying width are more likely to be perceived as moving toward the larger end, regardless of shape.Figure 4shows one type at a smaller scale: at this size the directionality becomes more apparent.</figDesc></figure>
<figure xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="fig_4"><head>Figure 3</head><label>3</label><figDesc>Three possible shapes for vectors, left to right: arrowhead, bulb, wedge. At this scale, the clear perception of direction is missing.</figDesc></figure>
<figure xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="fig_5"><head>Figure 4 A</head><label>4</label><figDesc>small region of a two dimensional field, displayed using the bulb representation.</figDesc></figure>
<figure xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="fig_6"><head></head><label></label><figDesc>Whatever shape is used for plotting vectors. the ori entation and length of two dimensional vectors can be unambiguously displayed. With three dimensional vectors, the orientation and length of the projection onto the plane of the page is clear, but both the length of the vector and the angle it makes with the plane of the page are unclear. Various approaches have been traditionally used in computer graphics to remove depth ambiguities. These include shading, depth cueing (in which objects closer to the viewer are shaded more brightly). and casting shadows. Of these, shading and depth cueing have heen shown to be the most effective on their own (two or more cues being more effective). For this application, neither of these is feasible. To maximize the amount of data on a page, we use vectors of maximum length on the order of 1/16". To provide meaningful depth cueing, we would need to provide roughly eight levels of grey, none of them too close to white. To get this many distinct levels of grey by haiftoning requires a sufficiently coarse screen that the lines would lose their shape. Hence, we use shadows to clarify the remaining components. Shadows are drawn in grey so that they are distinct from vectors. Bulb-headed vectors have the advantage that if the hulb is treated as a sphere, the shadow is the same shape as the vector. differing only in orientation and lengtht.</figDesc></figure>
<figure xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="fig_7"><head>Figure 5</head><label>5</label><figDesc>Bulb-shaped vectors with shadows. Bulbs are in the plane of the page, at grid points. Some of the thermometers completely obscure their own shadows.</figDesc></figure>
