<figure xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="fig_9"><head>Figure 6 A 3 Implementation</head><label>63</label><figDesc>test image showing thermometers displaced above the plane. The field orientation varies smoothly through all possible angles. Along the top and bottom it is coming out of the plane of the page; in between it rotates into the plane of the page and back. them. The displacement must be such that the shadows are near enough to their source thermometers to be easily associated, yet far enough distant that they are unlikely to overlap. We have two implementations: one for bit-mapped de vices, such a'i a screen or generic laser printer, and the other a PostScript® program. The PostScript program produces more compact output, so it is suitable for trans mission over a slow data line to a PostScript printer. Given a grid of vector values for a plane, the first step is to compute the projections of the vectors onto the plane and the shadows of the vectors' thermometer representations. This calculation is easily done by first transforming the plane of interest into the x-y plane -the projection of the vector is then just its x and y components (assuming it is viewed from the z direction).</figDesc></figure>
<figure xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="fig_10"><head>Figure 7</head><label>7</label><figDesc>The shadow is calculated as if the bulb of the thermometer were in the plane of the page. It is then translated on the page to make the thermometer appear to float above the paper (left). If the vector is directed into the page (iJ = [0,0, s,j), the translation required is exactly g (right).</figDesc></figure>
