<figure xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="fig_12"><head>1 �</head><label>1</label><figDesc>have described an algorithm for displaying slices of three dimensional fields on a bi-Ievel display. The algorithm is very fast, being limited by the speed with which BitBh operations can be performed. Vectors are represented as lines with filled circles at the head end. The presence of the circles eliminates ambiguity with respect to which end is the head. Depth is added by using shadows, leaving an ambiguity with respect to whether the vector points into or out of the plane. This last ambiguity is eliminated by displacing the plane of the vectors' representations from the plane of the page. Technically oriented observers tend to have no difficulty seeing the third dimension with the addition of shadows, once they are told how to interpret the image. It would be nice to have a method that needed no explanation. Figure 8 shows the utility of the algorithm in visualizing the field experienced by toner particles approaching an idealized photorecepter carrying an image of an X. At first viewing, images computed using our technique look like they need the addition of perspective. Two problems are introduced by the addition of perspective. First, we have already lost some of the magnitude infor• mation by showing only the projection onto the plane of the page. Some of this is regained through the magnitude of the shadow, but it is no longer possible to determine directly the ratio of the lengths of two vectors by looking at the image. Two components of the vector are preserved by the orthographic projection, so at least they can be � , , , , � , , , , .... , .... .... , , , \ \ \ , � , , , , .... .... , , \ , � ... ., ,,, , .... .... ,.... , '. .... .... .... , .... .... � , \ , 1 I I I I 1</figDesc></figure>
